For the sake of simplicity, let's assume that the `delta` values provided are always within valid ranges, though in a full implementation, you'd want to add checks to handle cases where adjusting by `delta` would exceed vector bounds.

### Forward Function

The `forward()` function moves a component towards the front of the `components_` vector by a specific number of positions (`delta`). This requires swapping the component with others in front of it, moving it closer to the start of the vector.

```cpp
void CImage::forward(int mylabel, int delta)
{
    int cid = getComponentIndex(mylabel);
    if(cid < 0 || delta <= 0 || delta > cid) {
        return;
    }
    // Loop to move the component forward by delta positions
    for(int i = 0; i < delta; ++i) {
        std::swap(components_[cid], components_[cid - 1]);
        --cid; // Update current index after swapping
    }
}
```

### Backward Function

The `backward()` function moves a component towards the back of the `components_` vector by a specific number of positions (`delta`). This involves swapping the component with others behind it, moving it closer to the end of the vector.

```cpp
void CImage::backward(int mylabel, int delta)
{
    int cid = getComponentIndex(mylabel);
    if(cid < 0 || delta <= 0 || cid + delta >= components_.size()) {
        return;
    }
    // Loop to move the component backward by delta positions
    for(int i = 0; i < delta; ++i) {
        std::swap(components_[cid], components_[cid + 1]);
        ++cid; // Update current index after swapping
    }
}
```

